Hello!

I often find myself using this mixin to test if collections consist of the same members:

``` javascript
_.consists([1,1,2,3], [3,1,2,1]);
// => true

_.consists([1,1,2,3], [3,1,2]);
// => false

_.consists('hello', ['o','l','l','e','h'], { a:'l', b:'h', c:'e', d:'o', e:'l' });
// => true
```

The common use case is to simply test if two arrays are equivalent ignoring order.  I've yet to find a terse way accomplish this using any combination of existing methods like `_.difference`, `_.intersection`, or `_.union` while handling:
- collections with duplicate values
- collections with non-primitive values

A couple more examples:

``` javascript
var a = { a: 'a' };
var b = { b: 'b' };
var b2 = { b: 'b' };

_.consists([a, b, b], [b, a, b]);
// => true

_.consists([a, b, b], [a, b, b2]);
// => false
```

Not sure if there's interest in this, but thought I'd share it nonetheless.

[Here's a more real-world example of how `consists` might be useful.](https://gist.github.com/jshanson7/98083803bddd66d21a90)

Somehow the arguments needed are mixed up in the following example:

https://jsfiddle.net/x3nury37/

``` javascript
function One() {};
function Two() {};

function matchesType(obj, type) {
    return obj instanceof type;
}

var fPartial = _.partialRight(matchesType, One);

console.debug(fPartial(new One())); // true, as expected
console.debug(fPartial(new Two())); // false, as expected

// so far so good, now it starts to get weird
var arr = [new One(), 3, new Two(), new Two(), new One()];
console.debug(_.find(arr, fPartial));

// matchesType: Uncaught TypeError: Expecting a function in instanceof check, but got 0
```

Strangely, it works perfectly if you add a hard version as well and call that one first (they both start to work correctly):

https://jsfiddle.net/x3nury37/1/

``` javascript
function One() {};
function Two() {};

function matchesType(obj, type) {
    return obj instanceof type;
}

var fPartial = _.partialRight(matchesType, One);
var fHard = function(obj) { return matchesType(obj, One); };

var arr = [new One(), 3, new Two(), new Two(), new One()];
console.debug(_.find(arr, fHard));
console.debug(_.find(arr, fPartial)); // now this works fine!!
```

